dmark legal cases. In discussions of Roe v. Wade, Bowers v. Hardwick, and the Hart/Devlin debates on decriminalization of homosexuality and prostitution, DeCew applies her broad theory to sexual and reproductive privacy, anti-sodomy laws, and the legislation and enforcement of morals. She finally discusses the intersection of privacy with public safety concerns, such as drug testing, and in light of new communication technologies, such as caller ID.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aPrivacy, Right ofzUnited States. 4aLegal History & Studies. 4aPhilosophy. 4aPolitical Science & Political History.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Archive Pre-2000z978311053617140uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978150172124340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501721243423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501721243/original  a978-3-11-053617-1  Cornell University Press Archive Pre-2000b2000  aGBV-deGruyter-alles